{{ 'ciem-care-system.css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}
{{ 'ciem-care-language-toggle.js' | asset_url | script_tag }}

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "HowTo",
  "name": "How to Service Your AAW In-Ear Monitors",
  "description": "The AAW care ritual: six considered habits for cleaning, drying, storing, and protecting AAW custom and universal in-ear monitors.",
  "step": [
    {
      "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": "Brush away the day",
      "text": "Use a soft brush to lift lint, dry skin, and surface dust from the shells, faceplate edges, and nozzle exterior. Always sweep outward, gently."
    },
    {
      "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": "Clear the sound bores",
      "text": "Use the included cleaning tool to lift earwax or dust from the sound bore openings. Work only from the surface; never push debris deeper."
    },
    {
      "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": "Care for cable contacts",
      "text": "Disconnect by holding the connector housing, never the cable. Inspect pins and sockets for lint or residue and brush them dry before reconnecting."
    },
    {
      "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": "Control moisture",
      "text": "Let the monitors air-dry on a clean surface before sealing the case. A fresh desiccant pack absorbs sweat, humidity, and stage moisture."
    },
    {
      "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": "Store without tension",
      "text": "Return clean, dry monitors to the protective case and coil the cable with a generous radius, so connectors and memory wire are never under tension."
    },
    {
      "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": "Bring repair to AAW",
      "text": "For universal nozzles with clogged mesh, or UIEM and CIEM shells with cracks, bring the monitor to AAW or an authorized dealer for repair or reshell assessment."
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<div class="ciem-care">
  <section class="ciem-care-hero" aria-labelledby="ciem-care-title">
    <div class="ciem-care-lang-switch" role="group" aria-label="Language selector">
      <button type="button" data-ciem-lang="en" class="is-active" aria-pressed="true">EN</button>
      <button type="button" data-ciem-lang="zh" aria-pressed="false">简</button>
      <button type="button" data-ciem-lang="zhHant" aria-pressed="false">繁</button>
      <button type="button" data-ciem-lang="ja" aria-pressed="false">JP</button>
      <button type="button" data-ciem-lang="ko" aria-pressed="false">KR</button>
    </div>
    <div class="ciem-care-wrap ciem-care-hero-grid">
      <div>
        <p class="ciem-care-kicker">AAW CIEM care system</p>
        <h1 id="ciem-care-title">How to Service Your IEM</h1>
        <p class="ciem-care-dek">Your AAW monitors travel close to the body — close to skin, sweat, and the rhythm of daily life. A few minutes of care after each session preserves the comfort of the shells, the openness of the sound bores, and the certainty of every connection. This is the ritual we recommend.</p>
      </div>
      <aside class="ciem-care-quick" aria-label="Quick care checklist">
        <h2>After every session</h2>
        <ol>
          <li>Brush or wipe loose debris from the shell.</li>
          <li>Check the sound bores before wax hardens.</li>
          <li>Let moisture evaporate before closing the case.</li>
          <li>Store the monitors and cable without tight bends.</li>
        </ol>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="ciem-care-system" aria-labelledby="ciem-care-system-title">
    <div class="ciem-care-wrap">
      <div class="ciem-care-system-head">
        <div>
          <p class="ciem-care-kicker">The ritual</p>
          <h2 id="ciem-care-system-title">Six habits that protect fit, sound, and longevity</h2>
        </div>
        <p>Work gently. Always clean outward from openings. Never force a tool into a sound bore — if debris is packed deep, stop, set the monitor aside, and reach out to AAW support. The care your monitors receive at home should always feel calm, never forced.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="ciem-care-step-list">
        <article class="ciem-care-step">
          <figure class="ciem-care-step-media">
            <img src="{{ 'ciem-care-05-brush.jpg' | asset_url }}" alt="Illustration of dust being brushed from a custom in-ear monitor shell" width="1183" height="1137" loading="eager" decoding="async">
          </figure>
          <div class="ciem-care-step-content">
            <span class="ciem-care-step-number">Step 01</span>
            <h3>Brush loose dust away</h3>
            <p>A soft brush lifts the day from the shells — lint, dry skin, surface dust — without ever pressing it deeper. Sweep gently outward across the shell, faceplate edge, and nozzle exterior, letting particles rise away from the seams rather than into them.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Brush outward from openings and edges.</li>
              <li>Avoid alcohol, solvents, and rough fabric on polished shells.</li>
              <li>Do this before deeper bore cleaning.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="ciem-care-step">
          <figure class="ciem-care-step-media">
            <img src="{{ 'ciem-care-02-clean-bores.jpg' | asset_url }}" alt="Illustration of a cleaning tool removing debris from custom in-ear monitor sound bores" width="2098" height="2016" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
          </figure>
          <div class="ciem-care-step-content">
            <span class="ciem-care-step-number">Step 02</span>
            <h3>Clear the sound bores</h3>
            <p>With the included cleaning tool, lift any earwax or dust from the openings of the sound bores. Work only from the surface — your monitors will tell you when something is too deep to touch, and you should listen.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Hold the bore downward when possible.</li>
              <li>Scoop from the opening; do not dig into the tube.</li>
              <li>Stop if the wax is hardened or lodged deep inside.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="ciem-care-step">
          <figure class="ciem-care-step-media">
            <img src="{{ 'ciem-care-03-cable.jpg' | asset_url }}" alt="Illustration of cable connector pins being cleaned before reconnecting" width="1183" height="1137" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
          </figure>
          <div class="ciem-care-step-content">
            <span class="ciem-care-step-number">Step 03</span>
            <h3>Care for cable contacts</h3>
            <p>Disconnect by holding the connector housing — never the cable itself. Inspect the pins and socket area for lint or residue, and clear any dry debris with a soft brush before reconnecting. A confident connection is a quiet one.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Never pull the cable itself to disconnect.</li>
              <li>Reconnect straight, without twisting the pins.</li>
              <li>Do not use liquid cleaner on exposed contacts.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="ciem-care-step">
          <figure class="ciem-care-step-media">
            <img src="{{ 'ciem-care-04-moisture.jpg' | asset_url }}" alt="Illustration of custom in-ear monitors stored in a protective case with a desiccant pack" width="591" height="568" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
          </figure>
          <div class="ciem-care-step-content">
            <span class="ciem-care-step-number">Step 04</span>
            <h3>Control moisture</h3>
            <p>After use, allow the monitors to rest on a clean surface and air-dry before the case closes around them. A fresh desiccant pack quietly absorbs the residue of sweat, humidity, or stage heat — protecting the acoustics from the inside out.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Replace desiccant packs when saturated or expired.</li>
              <li>Keep monitors away from heat, dryers, and direct sun.</li>
              <li>If exposed to water, disconnect the cable and let everything dry fully.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="ciem-care-step">
          <figure class="ciem-care-step-media">
            <img src="{{ 'ciem-care-01-store.jpg' | asset_url }}" alt="Illustration of custom in-ear monitors being placed into a protective storage case" width="591" height="568" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
          </figure>
          <div class="ciem-care-step-content">
            <span class="ciem-care-step-number">Step 05</span>
            <h3>Store without tension</h3>
            <p>Once the monitors are clean and dry, return them to the protective case. Coil the cable loosely, with generous radius — so the connectors, the memory wire, and the strain reliefs never carry the weight of a tight bend overnight.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Use the case whenever the monitors are not in your ears.</li>
              <li>Keep loose tools, keys, and metal objects away from the shells.</li>
              <li>Do not store monitors in pockets or bags without protection.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="ciem-care-step">
          <figure class="ciem-care-step-media">
            <img src="{{ 'ciem-care-06-service.jpg' | asset_url }}" alt="Illustration of mesh replacement and cracked shell repair for in-ear monitors" width="574" height="564" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
          </figure>
          <div class="ciem-care-step-content">
            <span class="ciem-care-step-number">Step 06</span>
            <h3>When repair belongs to us</h3>
            <p>Some attention belongs in the workshop. If the mesh of a universal nozzle becomes clogged with earwax, or if a UIEM or CIEM shell shows a crack, bring the monitor to AAW or an authorized dealer. We will assess the path forward — mesh replacement, repair, or full reshell — together.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Do not pick, pierce, or push through a clogged mesh.</li>
              <li>Use AAW or an authorized dealer for mesh replacement.</li>
              <li>Stop using cracked shells until they are assessed for repair or reshell.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="ciem-care-maintenance" aria-labelledby="ciem-care-rhythm-title">
    <div class="ciem-care-wrap ciem-care-maintenance-grid">
      <div>
        <p class="ciem-care-kicker">Service rhythm</p>
        <h2 id="ciem-care-rhythm-title">When to clean, when to rest, when to come to us</h2>
        <p>A few minutes of care after each session prevents most problems. Workshop service is reserved for blocked bores, loose parts, visible cracks, intermittent channels — anything that no longer feels right in your hand or in your ear.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="ciem-care-rhythm">
        <article>
          <h3>Every use</h3>
          <p>Wipe or brush the shells, check the bore openings, and let any moisture dry before the case closes.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <h3>Weekly</h3>
          <p>Under good light, inspect the cable contacts, the case padding, the desiccant, and every surface of the shell.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <h3>Send for service</h3>
          <p>Reach out to AAW if a bore is blocked deep inside, the fit changes suddenly, the shell is damaged, or one channel begins to drift in and out.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="ciem-care-support" aria-labelledby="ciem-care-support-title">
    <div class="ciem-care-wrap ciem-care-support-grid">
      <div>
        <h2 id="ciem-care-support-title">When it's time to bring them home</h2>
        <p>For blocked sound tubes, damaged shells, cable faults, or refit questions, reach out to our Singapore workshop before attempting anything aggressive at home. Whatever your monitor needs, our hands know the way back to its best.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="ciem-care-actions">
        <a class="ciem-care-btn" href="/pages/contact">Contact AAW</a>
        <a class="ciem-care-btn secondary" href="/pages/store-locator">Find a dealer</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>

